<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1866,2034]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis box="[151,265,1868,1891]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: Adult uropod with five segments; pleopod endopod with one subdistal inner marginal seta, pleopod 
<number box="[1422,1436,1866,1890]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" value="3.0">3</number>
basis with one inner seta; coxa of pereopod 
<number box="[639,653,1902,1926]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" value="1.0">1</number>
with apophysis; maxillule palp with five distal setae; maxilliped basis with one distal seta, coxa with two setae, endite with paired distal spines; cheliped fixed finger with five ventral setae; dactylus of male cheliped without spinulation along cutting edge; fixed finger with a slight (but not toothlike) proximal apophysis on cutting edge.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="56" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,453]" pageId="5" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis box="[199,297,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="56">Remarks</emphasis>
: All information on this species, collected from pylon-scrapings in Port Hobart, Tasmania, can be found in 
<bibRefCitation author="Edgar" box="[256,409,186,210]" pageId="5" pageNumber="56" refString="Edgar, G. J. (2008) Shallow water Tanaidae (Crustacea: Tanaidacea) of Australia. Zootaxa, 1836, 1 - 92." type="journal article" year="2008">
Edgar (
<number box="[340,402,186,210]" pageId="5" pageNumber="56" value="2008.0">2008</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. It is one of only two known species of 
<taxonomicName box="[875,1040,187,211]" class="Malacostraca" family="Tanaididae" genus="Hexapleomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="5" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[875,1040,187,211]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="56">Hexapleomera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to have five uropod segments; for distinctions from the other, see below. It also differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[795,912,221,245]" class="Malacostraca" family="Tanaididae" genus="Hexapleomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="5" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robusta">
<emphasis box="[795,912,221,245]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="56">H. robusta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having an inner seta on the basis of pleopod 
<number box="[151,167,255,279]" pageId="5" pageNumber="56" value="3.0">3</number>
, a distinct apophysis on the coxa of pereopod 
<number box="[684,698,255,279]" pageId="5" pageNumber="56" value="1.0">1</number>
, only five (as opposed to eight) maxillule palp setae, distal spines on the maxilliped endite, but no proximal tooth-like apophysis on the cutting edge of the fixed finger on the male cheliped. Apart from the number of uropod segments, it differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[987,1094,325,349]" class="Malacostraca" family="Tanaididae" genus="Hexapleomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="5" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="edgari">
<emphasis box="[987,1094,325,349]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="56">H. edgari</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having only one pleopod endopod inner seta, only one maxilliped basis distal seta, and only two maxilliped coxa setae. Finally, 
<taxonomicName box="[1292,1437,360,384]" class="Malacostraca" family="Tanaididae" genus="Pancoloides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="5" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moverleyi">
<emphasis box="[1292,1437,360,384]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="56">H. moverleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from all other known species of 
<taxonomicName box="[623,788,395,419]" class="Malacostraca" family="Tanaididae" genus="Hexapleomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="5" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[623,788,395,419]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="56">Hexapleomera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having no spinulation along the cutting edge of the dactylus of the male cheliped.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
